Package com.pranab.playwithgraphs.weightedgraphs.undirected

Class AdjancencyListUnDirectedWeightedGraph<V,​K,​W extends Weight>

java.lang.Object
com.pranab.playwithgraphs.weightedgraphs.undirected.AdjancencyListUnDirectedWeightedGraph<V,​K,​W>
Type Parameters:
V - - Value object that is encapsulated with UnDirectedWeightedNode to create a vertex
K - - Uniquely identify the new Vertex created.
W - - An entity that implements Weight so as to simulate strength of relationship as integer values.
All Implemented Interfaces:
Graph<V,​K>, UnDirectedWeightedGraph<V,​K,​W>, WeightedGraph<V,​K,​W>
public class AdjancencyListUnDirectedWeightedGraph<V,​K,​W extends Weight>
extends java.lang.Object
implements UnDirectedWeightedGraph<V,​K,​W>
An adjacency list implementation of the weighed Undirected graph. An undirected graph is graph, i.e., a set of objects (called vertices or nodes) that are connected together, where all the edges are bidirectional with varying edge lengths. This is realized by creating two edge between the source and target node,directed to each other. Graphs realization can be achieved through matrix or adjacency list. HashMap is used as an internal storage unit allowing unique key to identify each Vertex. Vertex is an instance of UnDirectedWeightedNode which encapsulates the value provided.
Author:
Pranab Bharadwaj

      finds the shortest path between two given Nodes/Vertex
      Dijkstra's algorithm implementation using min priority queue. Time Complexity : O(ElogV) V- vertices E- edges. However the implementation as of now isn't providing an tight upper bound as there is a call to minheap's getindex which runs with time complexity of O(n).
